5000|$|The Constitutions of Melfi, or Liber Augustalis, were a {{new legal}} code for the Kingdom of Sicily promulgated on 1 September 1231 by Emperor Frederick II. It was given at Melfi, the town from which Frederick's Norman {{ancestors}} had first {{set out to}} conquer the Mezzogiorno two centuries earlier. Originally a reform <b>of</b> the <b>Assizes</b> <b>of</b> Capua of 1220, themselves his reform <b>of</b> the <b>Assizes</b> <b>of</b> Ariano of 1140, the Constitutions {{formed the basis of}} Sicilian law for the next six centuries.|$|R
